<!-- ============================================================
  THE CHALLENGE (light bg)
============================================================ -->
<section class="cs-section cs-light">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="cs-two-col">
      <div class="cs-section-label-col">
        <span class="section-label">The Challenge</span>
      </div>
      <div class="cs-section-body">
        <h2>Competing for Enterprise Contracts with a Website That Looked Like a Side Project</h2>
        <p>
          NIS Consulting had built genuine expertise in cloud infrastructure, cybersecurity, and digital transformation for mid-market companies. Their delivery track record was strong, their team experienced, and their clients happy. But none of that came through when a prospect landed on their website.
        </p>
        <p>
          The site looked like it was built over a weekend on a generic WordPress theme. Stock photos of handshakes and server rooms. A contact form that sent emails to a shared inbox nobody consistently monitored. Service descriptions that could have belonged to any of the hundreds of similar firms on page two of Google. When they were shortlisted for a procurement process alongside boutique consultancies with polished, authoritative web presences, NIS were consistently at a disadvantage before a single meeting had taken place.
        </p>
        <p>
          Their entire business development relied on referrals and LinkedIn cold outreach. There was no SEO strategy, no content positioning them as thought leaders in cloud migration or cybersecurity, and no system to capture inbound leads. They were leaving the entire demand generation opportunity untouched while competitors built up organic search presence year after year.
        </p>

        <div class="cs-challenge-list">
          <div class="cs-challenge-item">
            <span class="cs-challenge-icon" aria-hidden="true">⚠️</span>
            <div>
              <strong>Generic look indistinguishable from hundreds of competing firms</strong>
              <p>Stock photos, template layouts, and service descriptions so broad they communicated nothing specific about NIS's actual capabilities or areas of focus.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="cs-challenge-item">
            <span class="cs-challenge-icon" aria-hidden="true">⚠️</span>
            <div>
              <strong>No case studies, no team profiles, no proof of work</strong>
              <p>Enterprise procurement teams need to see who they are dealing with and what outcomes a firm has delivered for clients similar to themselves. NIS had neither.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="cs-challenge-item">
            <span class="cs-challenge-icon" aria-hidden="true">⚠️</span>
            <div>
              <strong>Contact form going to an unmonitored shared inbox</strong>
              <p>Inbound enquiries were being lost or delayed by days. In enterprise sales, response time is a credibility signal. A slow reply after a prospect fills a contact form loses the deal before it starts.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="cs-challenge-item">
            <span class="cs-challenge-icon" aria-hidden="true">⚠️</span>
            <div>
              <strong>Zero SEO presence for any US enterprise IT keywords</strong>
              <p>Searches for "IT consulting New Jersey," "cloud migration consulting US," and similar terms returned zero NIS results. All organic demand was going directly to competitors.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>


<!-- ============================================================
  OUR APPROACH (dark bg)
============================================================ -->
<section class="cs-section cs-dark">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="cs-two-col">
      <div class="cs-section-label-col">
        <span class="section-label light">Our Approach</span>
      </div>
      <div class="cs-section-body">
        <h2>Build Credibility First. Rankings Follow Naturally.</h2>
        <p>
          Enterprise clients do not buy IT consulting services from a website alone, but they absolutely disqualify vendors based on one. Our starting point was understanding exactly which decision-makers NIS needed to impress: IT Directors, CTOs, and procurement managers at mid-market US companies with 100 to 1,000 employees. Everything we built was designed for that specific audience and how they evaluate vendors online.
        </p>

        <div class="cs-process-steps">
          <div class="cs-step">
            <div class="cs-step-num">01</div>
            <div class="cs-step-content">
              <h4>Competitor and Keyword Research for the US Market</h4>
              <p>Audited 10 competing IT consulting firms in the US market, including boutique specialists and regional generalists. Identified 60 target keywords, shortlisted 14 high-intent terms with realistic ranking potential within 6 months, and mapped content gaps NIS could fill with genuine thought leadership rather than thin service page copy.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="cs-step">
            <div class="cs-step-num">02</div>
            <div class="cs-step-content">
              <h4>Custom WordPress Design (No Templates)</h4>
              <p>Built a fully custom WordPress design with no off-the-shelf theme. The visual direction was deliberately positioned between the corporate formality of a Big Four firm and the approachability of a boutique specialist: authoritative without being unapproachable. Real team photography, specific service positioning, and a clear hierarchy of expertise signals throughout.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="cs-step">
            <div class="cs-step-num">03</div>
            <div class="cs-step-content">
              <h4>Case Study System and Team Profiles</h4>
              <p>Built a custom case study system with 6 published studies covering cloud migration, cybersecurity audits, and digital transformation engagements. Each case study follows a consistent problem-approach-outcome structure that enterprise evaluators can skim quickly. Individual profile pages for all 8 consultants with their specific areas of expertise, certifications, and a direct contact option.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="cs-step">
            <div class="cs-step-num">04</div>
            <div class="cs-step-content">
              <h4>HubSpot CRM Integration and Lead Routing</h4>
              <p>Replaced the unmonitored shared inbox with a HubSpot form integration that routes leads directly into the sales pipeline, assigns them to the right team member based on service interest, and triggers an automated acknowledgement within minutes. Every form submission is now tracked as a deal in HubSpot with full source attribution.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="cs-step">
            <div class="cs-step-num">05</div>
            <div class="cs-step-content">
              <h4>Technical SEO and Thought Leadership Blog</h4>
              <p>8 service pages optimised for US enterprise decision-maker keywords, technical SEO audit and cleanup across the entire site, and a blog set up with 4 initial articles on cloud migration strategy, cybersecurity frameworks, and digital transformation planning. Articles written to rank for long-tail queries that enterprise IT decision-makers search when they are in early research mode.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>


<!-- ============================================================
  WHAT WE BUILT (light bg)
============================================================ -->
<section class="cs-section cs-light">
